            <p:rationale>Federated identities are identities that the supplier of a service does not run. External organizations conduct their own user and password administration. From the point of view of privacy, it is undesirable to share this information. On the other hand, there is a need for cooperation with external systems. The manual ramp up of users and passwords from an external group produces a management burden, giving those users more accounts and passwords to remember and manage. Through the use of federated identities, external user administration remains with the organization where each user works. </p:rationale>
            <p:implications>Users and passwords are only administered in the organization where users work. The provider of a service / system offers federated users the ability to admit systems only from organizations they trust. There are infrastructural facilities available to exchange federated identities based on SAML 2.0 standard.</p:implications>
